The Warden's Wake
A Skyrim Investigation Adventure for 5-6 Players (Adept Tier)
Estimated Play Time: 6-8 hours (2 sessions recommended)
 Party Size: 5-6 players
 Difficulty: Scaled for Adept Tier (Party has 3-4 AP)
 Reward: N/A

Adventure Summary
In the smoldering ruins of Kynesgrove, the newly-chartered Skyrim Wardens have just witnessed their greatest ally abandon them and learned that their patronΓÇöHigh King ToryggΓÇöhas been murdered by Ulfric Stormcloak in ritual combat. The Civil War has begun, and the party stands at a crossroads. With Old Bjorn's steadfast loyalty and continued Imperial support, they must choose which crisis to address first: a race for a legendary crown, the corruption of a sacred grove, or a desperate rescue mission. Their choice will define their path forward and reveal the true scope of the threats converging on Skyrim.

PART I: The Aftermath & The Oath
Setting
The party's makeshift camp in the ruins of Kynesgrove, late evening. The dragon Sahloknir is dead, but its soul vanished mysteriously down the hill. Krusp Fanck has just departed into the darkness after declaring the party to be monsters unworthy of his company.
Opening Beat: Processing the Schism
Read Aloud: "The fire crackles, a small point of defiant light against the immense darkness pressing in from all sides. The sounds from the ruined village are a low, constant murmurΓÇöthe quiet weeping of survivors, the creak of makeshift shelters being erected, the whispered prayers to gods who may no longer be listening.
Krusp Fanck is gone. The legendary warrior who fought beside you against a dragon, who proved himself in blood and fire, has looked into your souls and found you wanting. His final words hang in the air like an executioner's blade: 'If I hear of you preying on the innocent, I will hunt you down.'
You sit in a tense, hollow silence. The victory against Sahloknir feels meaningless. You saved Kynesgrove from one monster, but in Krusp's eyes, you are simply different monsters wearing heroes' masks."
GM Notes: The Roleplay Window
This is a critical moment for character introspection and party dynamics. Give the players space to process:
How do they feel about Krusp's accusations?
Do they defend their choices or question them?
How do the "innocent" members feel about their vampiric companions?
Are there fractures forming in the party itself?
Pacing: Allow 15-20 minutes of open roleplay. Do not rush this. Their vulnerability here makes the next beat more impactful.

Bjorn's Declaration: The Oath of Loyalty
When the conversation naturally reaches a lull (or after 20 minutes), Old Bjorn approaches the fire. He's been tending to his horses and cart, deliberately giving them space, but he's been listening.
Read Aloud: "Old Bjorn steps into the firelight, his weathered face cast in sharp relief by the flames. He's carrying his travel pack and a rolled blanketΓÇöthe practical preparations of a man who has decided something important. He stops at the edge of your circle, and when he speaks, his voice is quiet but carries the weight of absolute conviction.
'He's wrong.'
The old man looks at each of you in turn, his gaze steady and unflinching.
'Krusp Fanck is a good man. A great warrior. But he's wrong about you. I watched you today. I've watched you since Winterhold. You didn't have to come to Kynesgrove. You didn't have to face that dragon. You didn't have to risk your lives for people you'd never met. But you did.'
He settles himself by the fire, pulling the blanket around his shoulders.
'The LanternsΓÇöit's a good dream. Maybe the only one this kingdom has left. High King Torygg saw something in you, and I see it too. You're not perfect. None of us are. But you're trying to do right by a world that's falling apart, and that's more than most can say.'
He pokes at the fire with a stick, sending sparks spiraling into the night.
'I'm staying. I'm with you. Whatever comes next, we face it together.'"
GM Notes: Bjorn's True Motivation
Unknown to the party, Bjorn's loyalty is reinforced by a secret terror. He felt the dragon's soul strike him earlier today. Something fundamental changed within him, and he doesn't understand it. But he knows, instinctively, that whatever happened connects him to the party's mission in ways he cannot yet articulate. His loyalty is genuine, but it's also rooted in a deep, unspoken fear that he needs them as much as they need him.
Mechanical Note: This scene establishes Bjorn as a permanent NPC ally. He will not abandon the party under any circumstances short of death.


